definition_en: Gnostic deity.

BM Definition: Personification of Abundance, or Plenty; usually a female figure with a cornucopia, and, especially in Roman imagery, a rudder.
Personification of the province of Achaea.

Son of Venus (q.v.) and Anchises (q.v.), father of Ascanius (q.v.); lover of Dido (q.v.); Prince of Troy and founder of Rome. At the request of Venus he was immortalised and became worshipped as the god Indiges.
Roman personification of fair-dealing. The Greek equivalent Dikaiosyne (justice or righteousness) is sometimes represented in the same manner.

definition_en: A spirit associated with the vineyards and grape fields in Greek religion; a companion of Tyche and a good spirit.

BM Definition: Young man from Catana (or Catania), Sicily; he and his brother Anapias (q.v.) saved their parents by carrying them away during an eruption of mount Aetna; both of the young men have been used as symbols of pietas and appear on Roman coins struck c.40 BC and featuring the portrait of Pompey the Great (q.v.) and on coins struck by the Republican moneyer M. Herennius (q.v.).

Young man from Catana (or Catania), Sicily; he and his brother Amphinomus (q.v.) saved their parents by carrying them away during an eruption of mount Aetna; both of the young men have been used as symbols of pietas and appear on Roman coins struck c.40 BC and featuring the portrait of Pompey the Great (q.v.) and on coins struck by the Republican moneyer M. Herennius (q.v.).
Lover of Venus/Aphrodite (q.v.), who bore him a son, Aeneas (q.v.); carried by the latter when fleeing Troy.

definition_en: (27 November, c. 111 – before 30 October 130). A Bithynian Greek youth and a favourite of the Roman emperor Hadrian. He died in mysterious circumstances on the Nile in Egypt and was worshipped as a god or hero after his death.

BM Definition: One of the twelve Olympian gods; goddess of love and fertility; mother of Eros/Cupid (q.v.), Anteros (q.v.) and Hermaphroditos (q.v.). Also used for the personification of the planet Venus.

definition_en: A sacred bull worshipped in Memphis in Egypt, son of Hathor. The deity was transformed into Serapis for Greek religion under Ptolemaic rule.

BM Definition: One of the twelve Olympian gods; son of Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.) and Leto/Latona (q.v.); brother of Artemis/Diana (q.v.); a major deity representing, in opposition to Dionysos/Bacchus (q.v.), the rational and civilized aspects of human nature; patron of the arts and leader of the Muses (q.v.); later, manifested as Phoebus (q.v.), he became identified with the sun-god Helios/Sol (q.v.).

One of the twelve Olympian gods; god of war; son of Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.) and Hera/Juno (q.v.); lover of Aphrodite/Venus (q.v.); brother of Bellona (q.v.); father of Romulus (q.v.) and Remus (q.v.). Includes the specific manifestation as triumphant, Mars Ultor. Also used for the personification of the planet Mars.
Dog of Odyseus/Ulysses (q.v.).
Daughter of king Minos (q.v.) of Crete; abandoned lover of Theseus (q.v); she was rescued by Dionysos/Bacchus (q.v.) on Naxos

One of the twelve Olympian gods; daughter of Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.) and Leto/Latona (q.v.); twin sister of Apollo (q.v.); a virgin huntress; symbol of chastity and protector of wildlife, also associated with helping women at childbirth; she later became identified with the moon-goddess, Selene/Luna (q.v.) and is sometimes associated with the goddess of the Underworld, Hecate (q.v.).

definition_en: Ascanius is a legendary king of Alba Longa and is the son of the Trojan hero Aeneas and either Creusa, daughter of Priam, or Lavinia, daughter of Latinus. According to Virgil, Ascanius was also called Iulus or Julus. The Gens Julia, or the Julians, the clan to which Julius Caesar belonged, claimed to have been descended from Ascanius/Iulus, his father Aeneas, and, ultimately, the goddess Venus, the mother of Aeneas in myth, his father being the mortal Anchises.
BM Definition: Son of Aeneas (q.v.) and Creusa (q.v.); fled to Latium with his father after the fall of Troy. However, according to another tradition, he was the son of Aeneas and Lavinia and was born in Latium. Founder of the city of Alba Longa. Sometimes called Iulus or Julus, which links him to the Julian family, who claimed to have descended from him and thus, by extent, from Venus.
God of medicine and healing; son of Apollo (q.v.).

One of the twelve Olympian gods; goddess of wisdom and just causes; patron of many civilizing arts, domestic crafts and the city of Athens; daughter of Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.), she emerged fully armed from her father's head. Pallas was a daughter of Triton and friend of Athena/Minerva (q.v.), with whom she sparred; one day Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.) intervened, standing in front of Athena with the aegid; Pallas, struck with fear, was not able to parry Athena's blow and was killed. In sorrow, Athena took the name of Pallas-Athena, carved a wooden statue of her friend (the Palladium) and placed it alongside Zeus. Athena is sometimes therefore referred to as Pallas in later depictions but these depications are in fact usually of Athena (i.e. a female figure with Corinthian helmet and shield).

definition_en: Consort of Cybele in Phrygian and Greek mythology. A god of vegetation.
Greek mythological hero, born in Corinth, who captured Pegasus and slayed the Chimera.

BM Definition: Personification of good outcomes of all human activities and especially of harvests.
Three-headed dog; guardian of the entrance to the underworld.
Personification of unanimity, oneness of mind, or an agreement between members of the Roman state. The Greek equivalent is Homonoia. Worshipped as a goddess by the Romans.
Mother-goddess, sometimes associated with Demeter/Ceres (q.v.), responsible for the total welfare of her followers; lover of Attis (q.v.).
Deity worshipped in Carthage in the Roman period.
One of the twelve Olympian gods; goddess of fertility and agriculture, particularly associated with corn; her daughter, Persephone/Proserpine (q.v.) was abducted by Hades/Pluto (q.v.).

One of the twelve Olympian gods; god of fertility, celebration, ritual and especially wine and intoxication; often associated with theatre; the 'twice born' son of Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.) and Semele (q.v.), his riotous nature is often directly contrasted with the sobriety and reason of Apollo (q.v.). Sometimes depicted with Ariadne (q.v.).

The twin gods Castor and Pollux; gods friendly to men and often saviours in times of crisis. Sons of Leda (q.v.) and Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.); brothers of Helen (q.v.) and Clytemnestra (q.v.); they abducted Phoebe (q.v.) and Hilaeria (q.v.), the daughters of Leucippus (q.v.).
God of love; son of Aphrodite/Venus (q.v.); brother of Anteros (q.v.); lover of Psyche (q.v.).

definition_en: Mother of King Minos of Crete. According to Cretan myth was abducted by Zeus in the form of a bull.

BM Definition: One of the nine Muses (q.v.); particularly associated with music and lyric poetry.

definition_en: Greek female spirit of prosprity.

BM Definition: Roman personification, particularly used to represent the fertility of the imperial marriage.
Goddess of happiness and good fortune, widely depicted on Roman coins as a personification of prosperity and success.
Goddess, perhaps responsible for converting the savage forces of nature for human use.
Fides is the Roman personification of good faith and loyalty depicted as a woman wearing a long chiton and peplos. See also Graces and one of the Theological Virtues.
Roman goddess of flowering or blossoming plants, mainly cereals. [Grk Chloris; married to Zephyr (q.v.).]
Roman deity and the personification or spirit of a person, place, institution or concept. Also widely used in modern iconography.

definition_en: Three minor goddesses of charm, beauty, nature, human creativity, and fertility: Aglaea ("Splendor"), Euphrosyne ("Good Cheer"), and Thalia ("Festivity").

BM Definition: Ruler of the underworld; brother of Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.) and husband of Persephone/Proserpine (q.v.).

A chthonian goddess of both benign and terrible aspect; protector of warriors, athletes, hunters, herders and fishermen; associated with magic, witchcraft, lunar lore, predators and other nocturnal creatures, doorways and crossroads; her rites often featured dog sacrifices and illuminated cakes.
Sun god; sometimes associated with Apollo (q.v.). Use also for personifications of the sun.

One of the twelve Olympian gods; god of fire and metal; lame son of Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.) and Hera/Juno (q.v.); cuckcolded husband of Aphrodite/Venus (q.v.); he forged the divine weapons of many gods and heroes and educated primitive men, teaching them the proper use of fire.

One of the twelve Olympian gods and chief goddess of the Greek and Roman pantheon; sister and consort of adulterous Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.); protector of women and patron deity of marriage and childbirth.
Celebrated hero; particularly famed for the completion of the Twelve Labours imposed upon him by Eurystheus (q.v.); deified at death. Sometimes called Alcides (descendant of Alcaeus).

definition_en: A god who combined Hermes (Greek mythology) with Anubis (Egyptian mythology). He is the son of Set and Nephthys, and was popular in Roman Egypt.

BM Definition: One of the twelve Olympian gods; patron deity of travellers and, subsequently, of commerce; also, sometimes, a trickster; son of Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.) amd Maia (q.v.); messenger of the gods and often a guide to mortals; protector of both shepherds and their flocks; later he became a personification of Eloquence and Reason; his image, the Herm, was often placed at roadsides to mark distances or boundaries. Specific manifestations include Hermes Psychopompos (as conductor of the souls of the dead). Use also for personifications of the planet.

definition_en: In Ancient Greek religion, Hestia (Greek: Ἑστία, "hearth" or "fireside") is the virgin goddess of the hearth, the right ordering of domesticity, the family, the home, and the state. In Greek mythology, she is the daughter and firstborn child of Kronos and Rhea.

BM Definition: The Roman personification of honour, worshipped jointly with Virtus (q.v.) in a temple in Rome.
Falcon-god who has many manifestations; son of Osiris (q.v.) and Isis (q.v.); 'Lord of the Sky'; symbol of divine kingship recorded in inscriptions as Good God.

Hygieia was the daughter of Asclepius (q.v.) and the deity and personification of health. The Roman goddess Salus came to be identified with Hygieia, encapsulating the safety and welfare of the state and the Emperor. Use also for the personification of Health in general.
The Roman personification of indulgence or mercy.

Goddess of immense magical power and symbolic mother of the king; sister and consort of Osiris (q.v.); mother of Horus (q.v.). [The name can also occasionally refer to private individuals (e.g. daughters of various kings, or high priestesses of Amun) but it is not currently possible to distinguish them in the collections of the Department of Ancient Egypt and Sudan.] Titles/Epithets (recorded in inscriptions as) - God's Wife of Amun and King's Daughter.

definition_en: The Roman personification of moral force in judicial systems.
Goddess of the iuvenes the novi togati, or men of military age.

BM Definition: The two-faced god of beginnings; guardian of doorways and gateways. N.B. The decorative feature referred to as a 'Janus face' is also recorded in the Description field in records for Oceanic objects where a face is shown on two sides.
Roman female representation of youthfulness appearing on coins. The legend is also used on coins to accompany a figure in military dress.

Titan (q.v.) and agricultural deity ruling on earth during the Golden Age; he castrated and deposed his father, Uranus (q.v.); father of Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.), by whom he and his fellow Titans were subsequently overthrown; later sometimes identified as the personification of Time (q.v.). Also the personification of the planet Saturn.

definition_en: An Aetolian princess who became a Spartan queen. She married king Tyndareus of Sparta and by him became the mother of Helen of Troy, Clytemnestra, and Castor and Pollux. She was admired by Zeus, who raped her in the guise of a swan.

BM Definition: Roman fertility god worshipped on the Aventine Hill in a triad with Ceres (q.v.) and Libera, his female counterpart. Sometimes associated with Dionysos/Bacchus (q.v.).
Goddess or personification of plenty and largesse.
Goddess or personification of freedom; particularly, in ancient Rome, associated with the freedoms and rights of the ordinary citizen. Often shown carrying the cap of liberty on a staff.

definition_en: A male representation of Luna, a moon deity worshipped primarily in Syria and Asia Minor. Also known as Mensis, he is typically depicted against a crescent and wears a Phrygian cap.

BM Definition: The eldest of the Pleiades; daughter of Atlas (q.v.), mother of Hermes/Mercury (q.v.). Later identified with the Roman Maia Maiestas and associated with Vulcan. Depicted on coins of Domitian (q.v.).
The most famous of the three Gorgons; the mortal sister of Sthenno and Euryale; decapitated by Perseus (q.v.); at the moment of her death, Pegasus (q.v.) and Chrysaor (q.v.) sprung from her head.
Roman personification of the concept of mind or understanding (sometimes as Bona Mens, 'good understanding'). A temple was dedicated to her in ancient Rome and she appears (rarely) on coins.

Roman personification of the mint, depicted on coins and weights. The mint was originally near the temple of Juno Moneta in Rome, from which it derived its name. Moneta is sometimes depicted in triplicate on medallions, representing the striking of gold, silver and bronze.
Goddess and personifcation of retribution.
Goddess and, more generally, personification of victory; messenger of the gods; she crowned victorious warriors, athletes and artists.
Personification of the River Nile.

definition_en: A divine spirit who animates or maintains Nature (natural forces reified and considered as a sentient being) for the environments where they live. Usually depicted as beautiful, young graceful maidens.

BM Definition: Personification of the River Orontes.

definition_en: God of fertility, alcohol, agriculture, the afterlife, the dead, resurrection, life, and vegetation in ancient Egyptian religion. He was classically depicted as a green-skinned deity with a pharaoh's beard, partially mummy-wrapped at the legs, wearing a distinctive atef crown, and holding a symbolic crook and flail.

BM Definition: God of shepherds, huntsmen and all inhabitants of the country; half-man half-goat; inventor of the flute. A related rustic divinity, Opaon Melanthios, sometimes associated with Apollo as a god of healing, is also depicted with similar iconography.
The personification of peace. Also a Roman deity, probably recognised as a deity for the first time by the emperor Augustus.

Winged horse; he sprung from the blood of the Medusa (q.v.) when Perseus (q.v.) decapitated her; the mount of Perseus (q.v.), when he rescued Andromeda (q.v.), and of Bellerophon (q.v.), when he killed the Chimaera (q.v.); he caused the the Hippocrene spring to gush forth with a stamp of his hoof upon a rock.
Roman personification of perpetuity.
Daughter of Demeter/Ceres (q.v.); carried away by Hades/Pluto (q.v.) to be his wife and queen of the underworld.
Son of Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.) and Danae (q.v.); hero, his deeds included the killing of the Gorgon, Medusa (q.v.), and the rescue of Andromeda (q.v.).
Personification of piety and Roman goddess of duty and devotion (as Pietas).
One of the twelve Olympian gods; brother of Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.); god of the sea and its inhabitants; protector of sailors; god and creator of horses.

definition_en: Rustic fertility god, protector of livestock, fruit plants, gardens and male genitalia. Priapus is marked by his oversized, permanent erection, which gave rise to the medical term priapism.

BM Definition: Personification of foresight; goddess of an official cult celebrating the imperial family's protection and care for the state.
Goddess who presided over chastity.
Son of Mars (q.v.) and Rhea Silvia (q.v.); mythological founder, with his twin brother Romulus (q.v.), of Rome.
Goddess; wife of Cronos/Saturn (q.v.); mother of Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.)
A vestal virgin and mother of Romulus (q.v.) and Remus (q.v.) by Mars (q.v.); later married to river god Tiberinus.
Goddess and personification of the city of Rome.

Son of Mars (q.v.) and Rhea Silvia (q.v.); mythological founder, with his twin brother Remus, of Rome. Abandoned as infants, they were suckled by a wolf, before being found on the banks of the Tiber. Later instigated the Rape of the Sabine Women in order to populate the new city.
Personification of the Fertility of the Age. An African god with the Greek name of Aion Karpophoros and the patron deity of Hadrumetum, depicted on Roman coins of the Severan period.
The personification of security.

Syncretic Egyptian and Hellenistic deity, combining the attributes of the gods Osiris (q.v.) and Apis (q.v.), his cult was associated with life after death and agricultural fecundity; subsequently conflated with many deities of the Greek pantheon: Zeus (q.v.); Hades (q.v.); Dionysos (q.v.); Helios (q.v.); Asclepius (q.v.).
A rural god and chief follower of Dionysos/Bacchus (q.v.).

definition_en: Roman tutelary deity of woods and fields.

BM Definition: A deity and personification of hope; particularly associated with the safety of the younger generation and, later, specifically associated with the imperial succession. Can be equated with the Greek deity Elpis.

Tarpeia, in Roman legend, a Roman woman who betrayed her city to the Sabines for what they wore on their left arms (their gold bracelets). As they entered Rome they crushed her under a mound of shields, which they also wore on their left arms. The Tarpeian rock at Rome, from which criminals were thrown to death, bears her name.
Youthful god of healing.
Earth-goddess and patron of the place of cultivation.

definition_en: The Greek personification of death.
Three minor goddesses of charm, beauty, nature, human creativity, and fertility: Aglaea ("Splendor"), Euphrosyne ("Good Cheer"), and Thalia ("Festivity").

BM Definition: Male personification of the River Tiber. Usually represented as a bearded river god resting on an amphora.
Half-man and half-fish; son of Poseidon/Neptune (q.v.) and Amphitrite (q.v.); also generic name for such mythological figures.
Protective deity of Gaulish origin.
Goddess of chance, fate, luck and fortune. Also a city goddess, usually depicted with a mural crown.
Goddess of the hearth and, more generally, of fire; her cult both expressed and guaranteed Rome's permanence; patron goddess of the Vestals. Often identified with the Greek deity Hestia (q.v.).
The personification of courage or valour. (Note: although Virtus should properly be depicted as a Roma-like female figure, the concept of Virtus is often symbolised by Mars)

One of the twelve Olympian gods and chief god of the Roman pantheon; specifically a god of the sky, he embodied all the benign and vengeful powers and functions of divinity; he led the other Olympian gods in their overthrow of the Titans (q.v.) and, as the husband of Hera/Juno (q.v.), is particularly known for his many infidelities. Includes the specific manifestations Jupiter Tonans ('Lightning Jupiter'), Zeus Keraunios ('The Thunderer') and Zeus Horkios (God of Oaths). Also includes the manifestation Zeus/Jupiter Dolichenus, originating in eastern Turkey. The term is also used for the personification of the planet. For depictions of the actual planet, see the Place Thesaurus.
Syncretic deity, combining the attributes of the gods Zeus/Jupiter (q.v.) and Amun (q.v.).
